{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"00598dd8-6f41-41fb-afaf-1160fecdc58f","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU trace (press Ctrl+C to stop)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in container), use the [standalone download](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#install) or copy the binary in via `kubectl cp`.\n- For production, collect for **30–60 seconds** under load, then `Ctrl+C`.\n- `kubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace` to pull the file out for analysis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ca03ad05-2131-4141-b379-3b436baabd62","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I should provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":338,"requestId":"7656:FD35D:183FC25:1BAA3ED:69FE8DCB"},"id":"36873234-8c29-4888-a520-9fe32f51ebe2","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:28:51.939Z","parentId":"e889f1e3-a6ac-47c5-9141-45a360e0f2cb"}
